Description:

This project is an Inverted Search system implemented in C for Linux operating
systems. The Inverted Search project is designed to efficiently search for
words across multiple text files using data structures like Hash Tables and
Linked Lists.

In this project, an inverted index is created where each word is mapped to the
files in which it appears along with the number of occurrences in each file.
Instead of scanning files repeatedly during search, the program builds a
database in advance, making the searching process faster and more efficient.

The Inverted Search allows the user to:

Create a database from multiple input text files
Display the complete indexed database
Search for a particular word
Save the database into a file
Update (restore) the database from a saved file
Exit the program safely

The project is developed using C programming language and demonstrates
the following concepts:

File handling (fopen, fscanf, fprintf, fclose)
Hash table implementation (size 26 for alphabets a–z)
Singly linked list implementation (Main node & Sub node)
Dynamic memory allocation (malloc, free)
String manipulation functions
Efficient searching techniques

